# Next Route Handler Standards

## Scope

- This rule applies to `app/**/route.ts` files, especially RPC proxy handlers under `app/rpc/`.
- These files are server-side request handlers, not React components.

## Proxy Behavior

- Keep proxy routes thin. Authentication forwarding, timeout handling, and backend error normalization should stay in `RpcClient`.
- Preserve the backend contract unless the task explicitly includes coordinated frontend + backend API changes.
- If a route simply forwards a backend endpoint, prefer `RpcClient.authenticatedRequest()` / `RpcClient.request()` over custom fetch logic.

## Request Handling

- Validate or normalize query params only when the proxy adds real value. Do not silently mutate backend parameters.
- Forward the HTTP method, body, auth headers, and content type explicitly.
- For passthrough responses, preserve backend status codes.

## Error Handling

- Network and timeout handling should remain consistent with `app/lib/rpc-client.ts`.
- Do not embed page/UI concerns in route handlers.
- Log only operational context. Never log tokens, cookies, or full Authorization headers.
